      = Canada\n|align       = right\n|width       =\n|state       =\n|shading     =\n|percentages =\n|footnote    = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/english/census96/data/profiles/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=1&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=35782&PRID=0&PTYPE=3&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=1996&THEME=34&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF= |title=1996 Census of Canada: Electronic Area Profiles |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2013-10-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923090414/https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/english/census96/data/profiles/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=1&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=35782&PRID=0&PTYPE=3&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=1996&THEME=34&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF= |archive-date=23 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|1871|3270\n|1881|5925\n|1891|16841\n|1901|20816\n|[[Canada 1911 Census|1911]]|31660\n|1921|38727\n|1931|39082\n|1941|42907\n|1951|51331\n|1961|54941\n|1971|61761\n|1981|64379\n|1991|71228\n|[[Canada 1996 Census|1996]]|73504\n|[[Canada 2001 Census|2001]]|74125\n|[[Canada 2006 Census|2006]]|78057\n|[[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]|80017\n|[[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]|85792\n\n}}\nThe population of Victoria was 80,017 in 2011. The Victoria [[Census Metropolitan Area]], comprising thirteen municipalities informally referred to as [[Greater Victoria]], has a population of 344,615 and is the largest urban area on Vancouver Island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMA&Code1=935&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=victoria&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=Census Profile \u2013 Census Metropolitan Area/Census Agglomeration |publisher=2.statcan.ca |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718101014/http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMA&Code1=935&Geo2=PR&Code2=59&Data=Count&SearchText=victoria&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |archive-date=18 July 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> By population, Greater Victoria is the 15th largest [[List of the 100 largest metropolitan areas in Canada|metropolitan area]] in Canada. The [[Capital Regional District, British Columbia|Capital Regional District]], which includes additional rural areas, has a total population of 345,164.\n\nVictoria is known for its disproportionately large [[retiree]] population. Some 6.4 percent of the population of Victoria and its surrounding area are more than 80 years of age\u2014the highest proportion for any of Canada's metropolitan areas. The city also boasts the country's third-highest concentration of people 65 and older (17.8%), behind only [[Peterborough, Ontario]], and [[Kelowna]], British Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070717/census_victoria_070717/20070717?hub=Canada|title=Victoria, B.C. a Mecca for elderly: census|publisher=[[CTV.ca]]|accessdate=2007-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018195936/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070717/census_victoria_070717/20070717?hub=Canada|archive-date=18 October 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> Retirees throughout Canada are drawn to Victoria's climate, scenery, year-round golf season, and pace of life.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}} A historically popular clich\u00e9 refers to the city as the home of \"the newly wed and nearly dead\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victoria.ca/common/pdfs/profiles_neigh_qa.pdf |title=City of Victoria Profile |accessdate=2011-11-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928161624/http://www.victoria.ca/common/pdfs/profiles_neigh_qa.pdf |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Ethnic origins===\n====Population by ethnic origin====\nNote: These categories are those used by Statistics Canada.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!Ethnic Origin<